    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-28T11:59:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-28T11:59:00-05:00" n="368"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/4–2854: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>, at Geneva</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d368fn1">Drafted by the Acting Secretary.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-28T12:59:00-04:00"
                            >April 28, 1954—12:59 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 15. <persName corresp="#p_RAW1"
                        >Radford</persName> and I had a long meeting with the President this morning
                    and <persName corresp="#p_RAW1">Radford</persName> gave a full report of his
                    discussion with <persName corresp="#p_CSWLS1">Churchill</persName>. He is
                    obviously greatly depressed by British attitude. I discount the natural military
                    reaction to lack of cooperation. However, the President’s decision is that all
                    requests made by <persName corresp="#p_PR1">Pleven</persName> will be met in so
                    far as it is possible to do so without undue risk.<note n="2" xml:id="d368fn2"
                        >Reference is to <persName corresp="#p_PR1">Pleven</persName>’s requests for
                        military assistance to France; on this matter, see telegram <gloss
                            target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 14, Apr. 27, <ref target="#pg_588">p.
                            588</ref>.</note> Am sending you later transcript of President’s session
                    with Congressional leaders on subject of Indochina as taken down by <persName
                        corresp="#p_CR2">Cutler</persName>.<note n="3" xml:id="d368fn3">For the
                        transcript, see telegram <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 16, Apr.
                        28, <ref target="#pg_599">p. 599</ref>.</note> The President is trying his
                    hand on a draft to <persName corresp="#p_CSWLS1">Churchill</persName> generally
                    in form of final appeal couched “more in sorrow than in anger”. When received
                    will transmit to you for suggestions. He does not anticipate much by way of
                    results, nor do I, but believe it is worth trying. There is obviously <pb
                        facs="0621" n="595" xml:id="pg_595"/> a definite blind spot in London as to
                    the trend of events in Asia.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
